I recently read a news item about a famous magician who converted religions despite the protests of his nephew. This is not to say that one faith is somehow more accurate or preferable to any other, but more to make note of how mutable our perceptions and reality may be. Even when it comes to those of us who create illusions for a living, there is no end to the new ways in which we are able to make sense of the crazy little corner of the universe we call Earth.  Alice in Wonderland is this bar’s namesake and it does not disappoint in this respect. Myriad beers, each with a subtle trajectory they might take you on. You may be someone who’s perfectly capable of doing calculus one moment. Give yourself a couple hours here and simple arithmetic may elude you. Wake up the next morning and the whole thing will have been like a dream.  I had a burrito. It did the (magic) trick.

The Ballroom proved to be a choice spot for a quick drink and meal prior to sitting down and watching the worst bit of screenwriting ever in the Game of Thrones finale. Unlike Jon, I went to this beautiful summery setting with my dog. We sat and ate on the patio with other patrons taking part in the old traditions of long tables where everyone sits at the same table. I had a point of cider and an amazing vegetarian burrito with a Mac and cheese side. I required more spice in both my burrito and my GoT finale... Unfortunately, I could only affect one of the two. Luckily, hot sauce, and other few condiments are brought to the table when food is ordered. The Mac and cheese was phenomenal! It needed no spice, pepper, or salt. The finale could have done without leaving me so salty, but that's not in this amazing establishment's control. I wish the finale could have been a tenth as good as The Wonderland Ballroom was. I do hope to visit again sometime and enjoy more of the company I had a pleasure to keep for a short while.

The Wonderland Ballroom is an interesting place. It's in what was an old row house/corner store in one of the older parts of DC and because of that is a lot smaller than you'd think some place called a Ballroom would be. To their credit they do make pretty good use of the space and the outdoor patio is quite nice.  The fixtures inside do need some repair though and the seats can be uncomfortable, particularly the small wooden folding chairs and teeny tiny tables upstairs.  By all accounts they do great with food and their beer selection is good, if smaller than you'd expect, even though PBR seems to be the astonishingly overpriced favorite.  The service is mediocre at best unless of course you are a regular. It's an experience and if you're older than the average age of their regular clientele you'll probably recognize some of the signs they have decorating the walls. Monday night trivia is quirky but pretty well done and definitely entertaining.

A northwest DC institution. It's been around a long time, so during the week you can enjoy the atmosphere--it feels like what a local neighborhood bar should feel like. The beer selection is great and the food (get the fried chicken sandwich and DEFINITELY the eggplant fries) is surprisingly good for what at first glance is a solid bar. The service is definitely slow, especially on the patio outside, but the best thing to do is go during the week on a Tuesday; it's not crowded, they have local stand-up upstairs, and it's super chill. Definitely nice to see a place like this at a corner full of row houses and local folks. What is potentially NOT good is the weekend sweaty dance party, unless that's what you're looking for, in which case it's great (music could use an upgrade)... wonderland does the switch pretty seamlessly back to its weekly chill however, so it gets 5 stars.
